Tokenize a mutable string with caller-owned state. POSIX.

Example workflow — strtok_r POSIX tokenization:
```c
#if !defined(_WIN32)
char *save = NULL;
for (char *token = strtok_r(line, ",", &save); token; token = strtok_r(NULL, ",", &save))
{
    printf("%s\n", token);
}
#endif
```

Example workflow — CSV simple split warning:
```c
char *save = NULL;
for (char *field = strtok_r(line, ",", &save); field; field = strtok_r(NULL, ",", &save))
{
    printf("field=%s\n", field);
}
```

Example workflow — key=value parsing:
```c
char key[64] = {0};
char value[128] = {0};

if (sscanf(line, "%63[^=]=%127[^
]", key, value) == 2)
{
    printf("key=%s value=%s
", key, value);
}
```

Example workflow — trim key value config line:
```c
char *equals = strchr(line, '=');
if (!equals || line[0] == '#')
{
    continue;
}
*equals = '\0';
char *key = line;
char *value = equals + 1;
/* trim whitespace before storing */
```

Bounded formatted output to a character buffer.

Example workflow — snprintf bounded formatting:
```c
#include <stdio.h>

char text[64];
int written = snprintf(text, sizeof(text), "Voltage=%.2f V", voltage);
if (written < 0 || (size_t)written >= sizeof(text))
{
    /* formatting failed or output was truncated */
}
```

Parse formatted values from a string.

Example workflow — sscanf parse:
```c
int id = 0;
double value = 0.0;
char unit[16] = {0};

if (sscanf(line, "%d;%lf;%15s", &id, &value, unit) == 3)
{
    printf("id=%d value=%f unit=%s
", id, value, unit);
}
```

Unbounded formatted output to a character buffer. The function cannot verify the destination capacity. Prefer snprintf whenever the buffer size is known.

Example — legacy compatibility only:
```c
char text[64];
int written = sprintf(text, "value=%d", value);
/* Prefer snprintf(text, sizeof(text), ...) for new code. */
```

Formatted I/O is split by destination and safety model:

- `printf` and `vprintf`: write to stdout.
- `fprintf` and `vfprintf`: write to a `FILE *` stream.
- `snprintf` and `vsnprintf`: write to a bounded character buffer and report the required size.
- `sprintf` and `vsprintf`: legacy unbounded buffer formatting; avoid for new code.
- `scanf`, `fscanf`, `sscanf` and their `v*` forms: parse formatted input. Use conversion widths for character arrays.

Example — bounded formatting:
```c
char text[64];
int count = snprintf(text, sizeof(text), "Voltage=%.2f V", voltage);
if (count < 0 || (size_t)count >= sizeof(text))
{
    /* error or truncation */
}
```

